Emotion categories, in my view, are made real through collective intentionality. To communicate to someone else that you feel angry, both of you need a shared understanding of "Anger." If people agree that a particular combination of facial actions and cardiovascular changes is anger in a given context, then it is so. You needn't be explicitly aware of this agreement. If you and I agree that a furrowed brow indicates anger in a given context, and I furrow my brow, I am efficiently sharing information with you. My movement itself does not carry anger to you, any more than vibrations in the air carry sound. By virtue of the fact that we share a concept, my movement initiates a prediction in your brain ... a uniquely human brand of magic. It is categorization as a cooperative act.

When computers process in time, we typically want them to also work in real time. For a performer on stage, however, there is no other option than running in real-time mode. The concert is happening in the "now," so the tools used need to run both in time and in real time.

Emotion categories, in my view, are made real through collective intentionality. To communicate to someone else that you feel angry, both of you need a shared understanding of "Anger." If people agree that a particular combination of facial actions and cardiovascular changes is anger in a given context, then it is so. You needn't be explicitly aware of this agreement. You don't even have to agree whether a particular instance is anger or not. You just have to agree in principle that anger exists with certain functions. At that point, people can transmit information about that concept among themselves so efficiently that anger seems inborn. If you and I agree that a furrowed brow indicates anger in a given context, and I furrow my brow, I am efficiently sharing information with you.
